    "notes": [
      {
        "componentKey": "n1",
        "kind": "pitfall",
        "text": "28 min is the floor; pull at the first sign of a set center with only a faint wobble and a golden top — the 3-egg + Greek yogurt base continues cooking as it cools, and a fully dry center at 35 min will be rubbery when sliced.",
        "stepKey": "s6"
      },
      {
        "componentKey": "n2",
        "kind": "technique",
        "text": "Whisk the eggs until genuinely light and frothy — 1–2 min by hand — before adding anything else; in a flourless cake the egg aeration is the main structural lift (the bit of baking powder only assists), and skipping it gives a dense, flat result.",
        "stepKey": "s2"
      },
      {
        "componentKey": "n3",
        "kind": "pitfall",
        "text": "Use room-temperature Greek yogurt; cold yogurt mixed into warm frothy eggs deflates the air you just built and can leave cold pockets that bake unevenly.",
        "stepKey": "s3"
      },
      {
        "componentKey": "n4",
        "kind": "technique",
        "text": "Fold the coconut in gently — it absorbs moisture during the bake, so overmixing at this stage tightens the batter and can make the cake gummy rather than tender.",
        "stepKey": "s4"
      },
      {
        "componentKey": "n5",
        "kind": "pitfall",
        "text": "The full 10-min rest in the pan is mandatory — this cake has no flour skeleton; slicing while warm tears it. Cool on a rack and run a knife around the edge before unmolding.",
        "stepKey": "s7"
      }
    ]
  }
